<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-794-662  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 794 662.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>CAD-CAM International  August 1989 v8 n8 p35(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Storage sees the light. (advances in optical disk storage)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Wignall, Eric.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Information technology demands a great deal of data storage.andO;Optical disks may be able to address that need with comparativelylarger storage capacities than magnetic media.andP;  Two types ofoptical disk storage devices have appeared on the market: WORM(write once - read many times) systems and magneto-optical drives.andO;The WORM allows only a single writing of data which cannot beerased.andP;  The drive requires software to police over costly errorsthat could easily occur, particularly in directory management andfile upgrades.andP;  Information entered on a magneto-optical disk iserasable, but takes longer to access.andP;  One technique to improveaccess time is changing a record to raster data.andP;  This worksespecially well in CAD-CAM applications.andP;  Disadvantages of opticalstorage include its cost and the loss of prior investment.andO;Optical storage technology is best suited to archiving.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Storage EquipmentAccess TimeWORMMagneto-Optical Disk DrivesTechnologyOptical DisksComparison.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotographchart.andO;Caption:   How laser beam recording and erasure works on a magneto-opticdisk. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>